The Kirkland lawyers proposed reopening discovery to allow Azar to depose t=
heir D.O.I. team.
Alsup basically responded, =E2=80=9CYa think?!=E2=80=9D He reminded Meta ab=
out the importance of timely and comprehensively producing records, noting =
that he=E2=80=99d previously warned that shortcuts could jeopardize their m=
otion for summary judgment. Given the lapse, he greenlighted a new round of=
 expedited discovery while postponing his summary judgment determination.

That judgment finally arrived on Monday, and it was mostly good news for Me=
ta. =E2=80=9CIt is concerning that Meta overlooked producing records,=E2=80=
=9D Alsup wrote in dismissing the case, albeit not on Section 230 or First =
Amendment grounds. =E2=80=9CNevertheless, =E2=80=A6 it does not move the ne=
edle; there is insufficient evidence to proceed past summary judgment.=E2=
=80=9D

A Porn Star Walks Into a Bar=E2=80=A6

The trial would surely have been a circus, and an embarrassing spectacle fo=
r Meta. At one point, Azar had thousands of porn actors on his witness list=
, identified by their stage names. Experts would have been called to opine =
on the adult entertainment market, executives would have been forced to rev=
eal=E2=80=94or adroitly obfuscate=E2=80=94their content moderation strategi=
es, and others would have testified about how the $1.4 trillion company ide=
ntifies and handles dangerous content. Meanwhile, Azar would have tried to =
prove that Meta consistently gave preferential treatment to OnlyFans perfor=
mers. In his brief opposing summary judgment, Azar said, =E2=80=9CIt is som=
ething like Schrodinger=E2=80=99s Playboy=E2=80=94they cannot say whether t=
here is going to be a naked centerfold until they open the magazine. Except=
 with OnlyFans, there is almost always
porn.=E2=80=9D

Meta had its own theories as to why OnlyFans got so much referral traffic f=
rom Instagram, pointing to endorsements from the likes of Beyonc=C3=A9. In =
any case, Meta will surely face more litigation over how it identifies and =
handles what it deems to be inflammatory content. That=E2=80=99s a story th=
at won=E2=80=99t go away with a single judgment=E2=80=94not for Meta and no=
t for any digital gatekeeper that holds sway over entertainers and influenc=
ers.

Yet the larger irritation for Meta has to be the Kafkaesque twist the case =
took=E2=80=94shifting the burden onto them to prove their innocence. Meta l=
oudly protested that most of the accusations were fabrications and had been=
 discredited during the litigation. Still, the case stagnated for over two =
years, with Meta fending off allegations until Alsup said he had =E2=80=9Cn=
o choice=E2=80=9D but to grant a dismissal. Up to that point, it was as tho=
ugh Meta had been mistakenly placed on a terrorism watch list. And yeah,
that really sucks.

Okay, thanks Eriq, I=E2=80=99ll be back on Thursday.

Until then,
Matt

