          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">In a strange twist =
of fate, the case was nearly resolved last spring, when <i>Azar</i> asked <=
i>Judge Alsup</i> for a dismissal. Having hit a brick wall=E2=80=94Meta cla=
rified that the plaintiffs, who included adult entertainers known as <b>Ala=
na Evans</b>, <b>Kelly Pierce</b>, and <b>Ruby</b>, were <i>not</i> actuall=
y on the terrorism watch list=E2=80=94Azar seemed to throw in the towel. He=
 conceded that class certification would be futile, further discovery point=
less, and, as a result, the suit lacked the jurisdictional legs to move for=
ward.<br/><br/>Yet, in a curveball, Meta <i>opposed</i> this straightforwar=
d dismissal. The social media giant wasn=E2=80=99t just looking to dodge a =
bullet; it sought a definitive win through its own summary judgment motion.=
 Meta=E2=80=99s lawyers didn=E2=80=99t explain their reasoning, but Azar to=
ld the court he suspected Meta was seeking to
establish precedent regarding Section 230, a ruling it could then leverage =
in other disputes over its content moderation practices.<br/><br/>But Alsup=
, intrigued by something Azar had included in his legal papers, wasn=E2=80=
=99t ready to shut the door on the case. Back in 2019, members of the Adult=
 Performance Artists Guild had stormed into Instagram=E2=80=99s headquarter=
s with a list of several thousand names of members who were protesting a su=
rge in content sanctions. Meta claimed it held no data or documents from th=
e period. =E2=80=9CWe may never know whether such manipulation of the [=E2=
=80=9CDangerous Organization and Individual=E2=80=9D list] occurred unless =
one of the whistleblowers and/or other sources who spoke with <i>Wired</i>,=
 the BBC, or other media sources come forward,=E2=80=9D Azar wrote.<br/><br=
/>Meta=E2=80=99s claim didn=E2=80=99t sit right with the judge. He demanded=
 Meta appear at a May hearing, ready to discuss the D.O.I. list and the pos=
sibility of dredging up an archived version. At said hearing,
Alsup didn=E2=80=99t mince words upon learning that Meta hadn=E2=80=99t sav=
ed the data. =E2=80=9CA company the size of Meta has something as important=
 as a D.O.I. list, and you make a conscious decision not to keep archived c=
opies?=E2=80=9D said Alsup. =E2=80=9CThat sounds nefarious to me, [like] yo=
u are destroying evidence before it=E2=80=99s needed. =E2=80=A6 I=E2=80=99m=
 suspicious. Your explanation, to me, raises more questions than it answers=
=2E=E2=80=9D<br/><br/>Then things got e=
ven worse for Meta=E2=80=99s legal cou=
nsel at Kirkland &amp; Ellis. At the hearing, Kirkland partner <b>Winn Alle=
n</b> explained the process by which Meta designates someone as dangerous. =
It starts with a nomination based on =E2=80=9Cevidence from reliable source=
s,=E2=80=9D he said, followed by a review by a team of employees across its=
 policy, content, communications, and legal departments, assessing the nomi=
nation=E2=80=99s validity. A final decision was made by a three-member lead=
ership group that, according to Allen, required unanimity. And the larger p=
oint? If any of the
adult entertainer plaintiffs <i>had</i> appeared on the D.O.I. list, there=
=E2=80=99d be tangible evidence of their nomination and discussion, or at l=
east some documented rationale for their subsequent removal.<br/><br/>A wee=
k later, Allen adjusted course. He admitted it was <i>technically</i> feasi=
ble to bypass the nomination process; that consensus <i>wasn=E2=80=99t</i> =
in fact necessary for inclusion on the D.O.I. list; and that, until 2019, r=
emoval decisions were made informally. When it came to the adult entertaine=
r Ruby, her content had been flagged <i>three times </i>by software designe=
d to check against internal counter-terrorism databases=E2=80=94likely fals=
e positives, Allen said. But Meta still couldn=E2=80=99t say, one way or an=
other, whether a match with a terrorism database resulted in any follow-up =
action. Perhaps more importantly, Meta hadn=E2=80=99t turned over any of th=
is in discovery. <br/><br/>The Kirkland lawyers proposed reopening discover=
y to allow Azar to depose their D.O.I. team.
Alsup basically responded, =E2=80=9C<i>Ya think?!</i>=E2=80=9D He reminded =
Meta about the importance of timely and comprehensively producing records, =
noting that he=E2=80=99d previously warned that shortcuts could jeopardize =
their motion for summary judgment. Given the lapse, he greenlighted a new r=
ound of expedited discovery while postponing his summary judgment determina=
tion. <br/><br/>That judgment <i>finally</i> arrived on Monday, and it was =
<i>mostly</i> good news for Meta. =E2=80=9CIt is concerning that Meta overl=
ooked producing records,=E2=80=9D Alsup wrote in dismissing the case, albei=
t not on Section 230 or First Amendment grounds. =E2=80=9CNevertheless, =E2=
=80=A6 it does not move the needle; there is insufficient evidence to proce=
ed past summary judgment.=E2=80=9D<br/></td>
